Newark flight delays

this is a study in collaboration with newark airport located in NYC there are 3 airports in this region. this will be both a comparative analysis on the performance of this airport versus its counterparts and also an analysis on natural phenomena that could be affecting the performance of the airport.

specifically, the performance metric studdied in this analysis is the delay of flights, both in frequnancy and in magnitude.

all airports had a similarly comparable rate of delays and asccociated magnitude of delays. however Newark airport appears to have slightly more delays as a percentage of total flights while also haveing a greater number of total flights when compared to the other two local NCY airports.

increased traffic may explain the increase in delay proportion.

weather data for this study was in incredibly short supply, the data for most relevant weather factors was missing to such an extent as to be useless and unreliable for this investigation.

visibility was the only viable statistic for use.

a correlation was discovered between the visibility and the magnitude of delays experienced within that visibility range. far visibility appears to reduce the probability that a flight will be delayed by a large margin.

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'day'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

no obvious increase in delays by day but a reduced overall volume on saterday. saterday also seems to have a reduced percentage of delays. reduced volume of flights could allow the airport to more easily manage delays.

long visibility seems to be a predictor for reduced delay magnitude. more apparent when plotted as an avarage of avarages however this may be misleading. while the data points seem to show a delay increase with longer visibility, the general trend of this distribution is slightly downward.
